The paper deals with algorithms for storing and manipulating objects in a physical array, which is a classic data structure problem. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses complexity bounds and NP-hardness results, which are typical topics in cs.AL (Computational Complexity) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity and Cryptography). The use of physical arrays and subintervals suggests a connection to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), while the relocation of modules is reminiscent of graph theory, which is covered in cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
